A dwarf planet is an object that is massive enough to be made spherical by its own gravity but has not cleared its neighboring region of planetesimals and is not a satellite. There are currently five recognized dwarf planets:
#[[Solar System/Ceres]] # [[Solar System/Pluto]] # [[Solar System/Eris]] #[[Solar System/Makemake]] #[[Solar System/Haumea]]
{{BookCat}}

Makemake, formally designated (136472) Makemake, was discovered in Mar 31 2005 by M.E. Brown, C.A. Trujillo, and D.Rabinowitz at [[w:Palomar Observatory|Palomar Observatory]]. It is the third largest known dwarf planet (after Eris and Pluto) and is the second largest known object in the Kuiper belt (after Pluto).
{{NOTE|Makemake is the mythological creator deity of [[w:Easter Island|Easter Island]] and god of fertility in the mythos of the [[w:Rapanui|Rapanui]], the island's native people. The name was chosen in part to preserve the object's connection with the fact as it was discovered a few days past Easter. As having a Polynesian origin, the name is pronounced MAH-kay MAH-kay.}}
==Orbit== Makemake averages 45.79 AU from the Sun, with an orbital eccentricity of 0.16. Its orbit is tilted 28.96° from that of Earth. Makemake takes 309.88 Earth-years to orbit the Sun.
==Rotation== Makemake rotates about its axis once every 7.77 hours.
{{BookCat}}

{{Knot-details | name=Zeppelin bend | image= Zeppelin Bend Final.jpg | names= Rosendahl bend | type= bend | strength= | origin= | related= [[Knots/Loop knots/Zeppelin loop|Zeppelin loop]], [[Knots/Bend knots/Hunter's bend|Hunter's bend]] | releasing= Non-jamming | uses= Connecting two ropes | caveat= | abok_number= }}
A '''Zeppelin bend''' is an all purpose [[Knots/Bend knots|bend knot]]: it is a secure, easily tied, and jam-proof way to connect two ropes. Though its simplicity and security may be matched by other bends, it is unique in the ease with which it is untied, even after heavy loading. It is also referred to as a "Rosendahl bend", both names stemming from its use to moor airships (''[[wikt:Zeppelin|Zeppelin]]'' being a type of airship, and [[w:Charles Rosendahl|Charles Rosendahl]] being the airship captain who popularized this bend by insisting it be used to moor his craft). Despite being praised by some sources as "the perfect bend knot", the knot is not very well-known; [[w:Clifford Ashley|Clifford Ashley]], author of ''[[w:The Ashley Book of Knots|The Ashley Book of Knots]]'', was apparently unaware of this bend.
==Tying== [[Image:Zeppelin Bend HowTo.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Zeppelin bend step by step]] * Form a [[:File:BightLoopElbow.jpg|loop]] in each of the ends of rope * Overlay one loop on the other, such that the working end of each rope faces "outwards" or away from the other hitch * Pull either loose end once around the loop in the other rope, and then through the "tunnel" created by the two hitches * Repeat with the other loose end * Pull on all four rope parts to tighten the knot. * To untie, pull simultaneously on the two turns that go round the standing parts.
==External links== *[http://notableknotindex.webs.com/Zeppelin.html Description of the Zeppelin Bend on Notable Knot Index]
{{BookCat}}

